---
title: Why I Switched to Markdoc
author: Mark Syntax
date: 2025-10-29
---


Writing docs shouldn't feel like fighting your syntax. For years I kept duct-taping Markdown plugins together to handle variables, shared layouts, and conditional content, and every hack made the docs a little harder to maintain.

{% callout type="note" %}
Markdoc supports variables, tags,  and reusable layouts while staying readable.
{% /callout %}

## Cleaner Writing

Markdown is great, but when you need reusable layouts, **Markdoc** scales better. Once my docs grew past a handful of pages, I needed a system that let me reuse components, keep content in sync, and keep authoring approachable for the rest of the team.

{% code lang="markdown" %}
{% callout type="info" %}
Documentation is better when it's composable.
{% /callout %}
{% /code %}

- Built in components stay readable in plain text.
- Writers can work in Markdown and still rely on dynamic data.
- Reviewers understand intent because the structure is explicit.

## Structured Content Without Plugins

Most static site tools forced us to install brittle plugins to support advanced layouts. Markdoc gives us syntactic sugar via tags and conditional logic without sacrificing clarity, so the authoring experience stays predictable.

{% callout type="warning" %}
Before migrating, audit custom Markdown extensions. Many of them map cleanly to Markdoc tags or partials.
{% /callout %}

> "Docs should empower, not intimidate." That mantra shaped our migration plan and guided which features we shipped first.

### What Migration Looked Like

1. Inventory Markdown shortcodes and custom components.
2. Convert repeated patterns into Markdoc tags with shared partials.
3. Publish a style guide so contributors know when to reach for tags versus raw Markdown.
4. Add automated previews to catch visual or structural regressions early.

